		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">One of the main reasons for the still scarce use of model-checking technology by the software industry is the fact that model-checking has focused mostly on the analysis of systems with a possibly large but finite number of states. This is appropriate for hardware, but hot for software, where even the simplest systems have an infinite state space. Infinities are caused both by control (possibly recursive procedures, process creation, and by data (integer variables, lists). Previous research has shown that an automata-theoretic approach can solve the problems raised by possibly recursive procedures, and it has lead to the design and implementation of the MOPED model-checker.The proposed research aims at- adding symbolic techniques to MOPED for dealing with infinities caused by data structures;- extending the automata-theoretic approach (and its implementation in MOPED) to the problems raised by multithreaded programs with communication between threads;- applying the new version of MOPED to the verification of drivers (written in C) and to the analysis of security properties in Java code.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
